    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_451273625" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/451273625" />
    <a title="Ben" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4796031-ben"><img alt="Ben" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627534823p2/4796031.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/451273625?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben" href="/user/show/4796031-ben">Ben</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer451273625" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10131017941336872959">&apos;What I Believe&apos; is a remarkable essay on humanism and personal philosophies of Bertrand Russell. Originally published in 1925, it&apos;s just as relevant today. His simple yet elegant style should be a guide for anyone interested in disseminating clear ideas and sound opinions. <br/><br/>Russell, in this elegant paragraph sums up his idea of what constitutes a life well-lived:<br/><blockquote>My view is this:<br/><br/>The good life is one inspired by love and guided by knowledge. Knowledge and love are both indefinitely extensible; the</blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText10131017941336872959" style="display:none">'What I Believe' is a remarkable essay on humanism and personal philosophies of Bertrand Russell. Originally published in 1925, it's just as relevant today. His simple yet elegant style should be a guide for anyone interested in disseminating clear ideas and sound opinions. <br /><br />Russell, in this elegant paragraph sums up his idea of what constitutes a life well-lived:<br /><blockquote>My view is this:<br /><br />The good life is one inspired by love and guided by knowledge. Knowledge and love are both indefinitely extensible; therefore, however good a life may be, a better life can be imagined. Neither love without knowledge, nor knowledge without love can produce a good life.</blockquote><br />The great champion of humanism and rational thought he is, he goes into some more details on some of the more classical human rights and ethical issues. For instance, on the criminal justice system, he maintains:<br /><blockquote>Suffering to the criminal can never be justified by the notion of vindictive punishment. If education combined with kindness is equally effective, it is to be preferred; still more is it to be preferred if it is more effective.</blockquote><br />He put a great emphasis on science and research in contrast to belief and dogma, as our main tool at hand, to improve and better the condition of humankind. <br /><blockquote>An able physician is more useful to a patient than the most devoted friend, and progress in medical knowledge does more for the health of the community than ill-informed philanthropy. For example, the spread of cancer is alarming—what are we to do about it? At the moment, no one can answer the question for lack of knowledge; and the knowledge is not likely to emerge except through endowed research. <br /></blockquote><br />This timeless 40 pages classic is well worth a read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10131017941336872959" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


