<div id="review_442192715" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/442192715" />
    <a title="Jude" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11919813-jude"><img alt="Jude" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/442192715?book_show_action=true">Oct 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jude" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jude" href="/user/show/11919813-jude">Jude</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer442192715" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8478118808356944350">This essay was only 40 pages long, but in that 40 pages Bertrand Russell managed to pack in lots of thought provoking ideas. Since it was a library book, I felt duty bound to make notes of some of his more noteworthy quotes. I can see why this book made the establishment so unhappy. He turns lots of ideas that we take on board so uncritically and makes you question them. It is not just religion that he has in his sights, but also morality, our treatment of criminals and education. <br/>Whether you ul</span>
  <span id="freeText8478118808356944350" style="display:none">This essay was only 40 pages long, but in that 40 pages Bertrand Russell managed to pack in lots of thought provoking ideas. Since it was a library book, I felt duty bound to make notes of some of his more noteworthy quotes. I can see why this book made the establishment so unhappy. He turns lots of ideas that we take on board so uncritically and makes you question them. It is not just religion that he has in his sights, but also morality, our treatment of criminals and education. <br />Whether you ultimately agree with his views or not, this essay is guaranteed to make you sit down and examine what you do believe, and that can only be a good thing to do from time to time. His opening gambit: "If there is a god, he, she, it, or they should be tried for crimes against humanity. The devout are guilty of praising wickedness, either because they are too cowardly to face the fact that god is a criminal,or because they have a perverted sense of morality and really believe that might makes right." is going to have the deeply religious outraged I am sure. He doesn't argue about proof or lack of for the existence of god, but he certainly argues against all the manifest pain that we have inflected on ourselves and our neighbours because of a belief in god.<br />On the subject of education:"In all stages of education the influence of superstition is disastrous. A certain percentage of children have the habit of thinking; one of the aims of education is to cure them of this habit." That remark is certainly contentious and was no doubt the reason his fitness to teach was called into question back in the 1920's.As for his beliefs concerning the treatment and rehabilitation of criminals, his arguments are such that they could cause the fiercest debates to this day.<br />I would recommend this essay to anybody who is interested in the way our societies are formed and it was interesting to see how much of our thinking has changed/stayed the same since he wrote this book.His views were way before his time, and even today would be the source of in depth debate.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8478118808356944350" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


