<div id="review_1012548031" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1012548031" />
    <a title="Samuel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7336012-samuel"><img alt="Samuel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595715078p2/7336012.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1012548031?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Samuel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Samuel" href="/user/show/7336012-samuel">Samuel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7336012-samuel?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1012548031" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1624409347473273543">I am a false book reader, in the sense that the main reason why I read books is not because I enjoy the simple and fundamental feeling it gives to most readers - the feeling of travelling to a different world; the true journey of plunging into a universe that is not our own. Now, I immensely enjoy journeys, but the main reason I read books is because of the ideas within them. I praise ideas higher than anything else - above the thrill of discovering whether a character will die in the next page,</span>
  <span id="freeText1624409347473273543" style="display:none">I am a false book reader, in the sense that the main reason why I read books is not because I enjoy the simple and fundamental feeling it gives to most readers - the feeling of travelling to a different world; the true journey of plunging into a universe that is not our own. Now, I immensely enjoy journeys, but the main reason I read books is because of the ideas within them. I praise ideas higher than anything else - above the thrill of discovering whether a character will die in the next page, the magnanimous and unique descriptions or the author's brilliant writing style. To read books and fail to experience new ideas, thoughts (either from the author or the reader him/herself), or additionally miss the opportunity to properly think on those ideas for your betterment, is a waste of time to me.<br /><br />Russell is full of ideas, most of them with a great practical utility; his mind resembles a blade, sharpened by thought and experiences throughout the years, and he holds it and swings it with a firm grip and cunning skill. Russell is generally a very easy and light read, despite the controversial and non-trivial issues that he purports to address. However, I feel that most of the topics addressed were incomplete, in the sense that they would require a more extensive description, mainly on his philosophy regarding the Good Life. Happiness, as Russell suggests, should be triggered by emotion and guided by reason - in most respects, I couldn't agree more, although I could pose some objections which he doesn't even hint at explaining in the book. Moreover, I feel like some ideas and sections are disorganized and a summary at the end of each chapter would be welcome (I have made this same criticism regarding A History of Western Philosophy).<br /><br />I am almost at the end of my useless rant. I usually find it very hard to disagree with Russell, and when we disagree, it's not very strongly. This is both bad and good:<br /><br />/ This is bad, because as I said, I enjoy the sprouting of new ideas and discussions, and if I already agree with him on most issues, I am not learning nor thinking on anything new.<br />/ This is good, because I am strongly convinced that he was a human being of the highest caliber, both compassionate and rational, which is precisely why I struggle so much to disagree (although this does not mean we agree on everything, nor that I don't think the same good things of someone with whom I disagree on many topics). <br /><br />The world needs people like him, who are less interested in individualistic short-term satisfaction that comes from unjustified beliefs, or from stagnant, never-changing personalities who cannot come to terms with their own sensible ego when faced with change and criticism, and more interested in long-term happiness and flourishment of mankind.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1624409347473273543" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

