<div id="review_1000027276" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1000027276" />
    <a title="Ollie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9892350-ollie"><img alt="Ollie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1430942105p2/9892350.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1000027276?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ollie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ollie" href="/user/show/9892350-ollie">Ollie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/20130765-what-i-believe">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1000027276" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15633463569433308652">One of the great things about our anarchist approach here on Ground Control is that it gives us the opportunity to stay creative with our columns. After all, isn’t pop culture consumption supposed to be creative, and aren’t we allowed to stay fresh? So, it is with great pleasure that we’re going to be doing something a little bit different with I Wanna Be Literated! (and hopefully not the only time) and do an entire series on the writings of Bertrand Russell.<br/><br/>Russell was a world renown philosophe</span>
  <span id="freeText15633463569433308652" style="display:none">One of the great things about our anarchist approach here on Ground Control is that it gives us the opportunity to stay creative with our columns. After all, isn’t pop culture consumption supposed to be creative, and aren’t we allowed to stay fresh? So, it is with great pleasure that we’re going to be doing something a little bit different with I Wanna Be Literated! (and hopefully not the only time) and do an entire series on the writings of Bertrand Russell.<br /><br />Russell was a world renown philosopher, mathematician, historian, political activist and humanist who’s influential writings (and what writings they are) varied on a wide arrange of topics. And scaringly so. And the fact that Noam Chomsky has a giant picture of him hanging on his wall is reason enough to expose a new generation to the thoughts of this wonderful man. Luckily, that is exactly what Routledge is doing and collecting, conveniently so, Russell’s writings by topical categories. <br /><br />Starting things off is his book What I Believe, a short essay in which Russell briefly touches on what he believes in necessary to lead “the good life.” Although he has previously written on his disappointment in humanity in his book Icarus, What I Believe has more positive undertones. It essentially empowers humanity and argues that it can take greater control over the happiness in its life by focusing on leading a life consisting of love and knowledge. Both are necessary, although love more so since Russell argues that the possession of love leads one to seek knowledge, anyhow. A life based on love nurtures cooperation and equality while the acquisition of knowledge allows us to cast off some of the chains of slavery (like religion). In addition, we should follow our “morals” only insofar as they allow us to live happily in a community despite our differences. Powerful stuff and the perfect primer for anyone curious as to Bertrand Russell’s writings.<br /><br />This edition of What I Believe also includes some supplementary material by Russell such as a brief exploration of how he writes (and the simple rules he follows when doing so) and why he took to philosophy (as one would guess, to find truths in life) both of which are written in Russell’s characteristic wit.<br /><br />Russell has had a remarkable body of work and it is difficult to figure out where curious minds should start. Might I suggest What I Believe.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15633463569433308652" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


