<div id="review_4133395733" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4133395733" />
    <a title="Richard Thompson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11657479-richard-thompson"><img alt="Richard Thompson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530711053p2/11657479.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4133395733?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard Thompson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard Thompson" href="/user/show/11657479-richard-thompson">Richard Thompson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11657479-richard-thompson?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11657479-richard-thompson?shelf=religion-spiritual">religion-spiritual</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4133395733" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4589621214376265411">I like a good manifesto. This one was considered radical in its day. It was quoted against Russell in a trial to prove him unfit to teach. But it is tame reading today. He&apos;s an atheist. So what. Some of Russell&apos;s ideas that were advanced at the time are commonly accepted today, but other parts of it feel dated. His faith in rational science as a basis for human progress is not as much of an article of faith today as it was in his time. He says that the good life has to be based on love guided by</span>
  <span id="freeText4589621214376265411" style="display:none">I like a good manifesto. This one was considered radical in its day. It was quoted against Russell in a trial to prove him unfit to teach. But it is tame reading today. He's an atheist. So what. Some of Russell's ideas that were advanced at the time are commonly accepted today, but other parts of it feel dated. His faith in rational science as a basis for human progress is not as much of an article of faith today as it was in his time. He says that the good life has to be based on love guided by knowledge, but then almost as a footnote he adds that of course it's also nice to have a comfortable income and get a good education. He has compassion for the poor and people of color, but it comes off as being more than a little paternalistic. And then let's take a look at Russell on love. He may have had a lot of lovers, but he was hardly a paragon of virtue with his wives and children. And knowledge? This was the guy who came up with the paradox of the barber who shaves everyone who doesn't shave himself. He should have known that knowledge is not built on firm bedrock. So some of what he advocates doesn't ring very true. And his view of the good life does not seem to include happiness, broad experience, admirable action, service to others or spiritual fulfillment. He was missing out on a lot. It's a step up from pure Benthamite utilitarianism, but not by a lot.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4589621214376265411" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

